<div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"><h3>March 2022</h3><div name="1.GOVERNINGTEXTS" data-unique="1.GOVERNINGTEXTS"></div><h2>1. GOVERNING TEXTS </h2><div name="1.1.Legislation" data-unique="1.1.Legislation"></div><h3>1.1. Legislation </h3><ul><li>Recitals 4, 75, 76, 84, 90 and 92 and Article 35 of the  <a href="https://platform.dataguidance.com/cross-border-charts/general-data-protection-regulation" target="_blank">General Data Protection Regulation (Regulation (EU) 2016/679)</a> ('GDPR')  </li><li>Articles 62, 63, 66 and 90 of Act No.78-17 of 6 January 1978 on Data Processing, Data Files and Individual Liberties (as amended to implement the GDPR) (only available in French <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/fr/la-loi-informatique-et-libertes" target="_blank">here</a>) ('the Act'). You can find an unofficial translation of the Act <a href="https://platform.dataguidance.com/legal-research/act-no78-17-6-january-1978-data-processing-data-files-and-individual-liberties-0" target="_blank">here</a>.</li></ul><div name="1.2.RegulatoryAuthorityGuidance" data-unique="1.2.RegulatoryAuthorityGuidance"></div><h3>1.2. Regulatory Authority Guidance &nbsp; &nbsp;</h3><p>The<a href="https://ec.europa.eu/newsroom/article29/news.cfm?item_type=1358" target="_blank"> Article 29 Working Party </a>('WP29') has issued the following guidance:</p><ul><li><a href="https://platform.dataguidance.com/legal-research/guidelines-data-protection-impact-assessment-dpia-and-determining-whether-0" target="_blank">Guidelines on Data Protection Impact Assessment </a>('DPIA') ('the Guidelines')</li></ul><p>The <a href="https://edpb.europa.eu/" target="_blank">European Data Protection Board</a> ('EDPB') has replaced the WP29 and has endorsed the Guidelines.</p><p>The <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/" target="_blank">French data protection authority</a> ('CNIL') has published the following guidelines relevant to DPIAs:</p><ul><li>Analysis of DPIAs (only available in French <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/fr/RGPD-analyse-impact-protection-des-donnees-aipd" target="_blank">here</a>);</li><li>Privacy Impact Assessment ('PIA') Method of February 2018 (only available in French <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/sites/default/files/atoms/files/cnil-pia-1-fr-methode.pdf" target="_blank">here</a>);</li><li><a href="https://www.dataguidance.com/legal-research/privacy-impact-assessment-pia-knowledge-bases" target="_blank">PIA Knowledge Bases&nbsp;of February 2018</a> (available in French <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/sites/default/files/atoms/files/cnil-pia-3-fr-basesdeconnaissances.pdf" target="_blank">here</a>);</li><li>A know-how on DPIA (only available in French <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/fr/ce-quil-faut-savoir-sur-lanalyse-dimpact-relative-la-protection-des-donnees-aipd" target="_blank">here</a>);&nbsp;</li><li>Deliberation No. 2018-326 of 11 October 2018 adopting guidelines on DPIA provided for by the GDPR (only available in French <a href="https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000037559518&amp;dateTexte=&amp;categorieLien=id" target="_blank">here</a>); and&nbsp;</li><li>Infographic: Do I need to conduct a DPIA? (only available in French <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/sites/default/files/atoms/files/infographie_aipd.pdf" target="_blank">here</a>).</li></ul><p>The CNIL has issued a list of activities which require ('Blacklist') and a list of activities that do&nbsp;not require ('Whitelist') a DPIA:</p><ul><li><a href="https://platform.dataguidance.com/legal-research/deliberation-n%C2%B0-2018-327-11-octobre-2018-adoption-list-processing-operations-which" target="_blank">France DPIA Blacklist</a> ('the France Blacklist'); and</li><li><a href="https://platform.dataguidance.com/legal-research/deliberation-no-2019-118-12-september-2019-adoption-list-kind-processing-operations" target="_blank">France DPIA<em> </em>Whitelist</a> ('the France Whitelist').</li></ul><p>Furthermore, the EDPB has published the following Opinions for France:</p><ul><li><a href="https://www.dataguidance.com/legal-research/opinion-72020-draft-list-competent-supervisory-authority-france-regarding-processing">Opinion 7/2020 on the draft list of the competent supervisory authority of France regarding the processing operations exempt from the requirement of a data protection impact assessment (Article 35(5) GDPR)</a>;</li><li><a href="https://platform.dataguidance.com/legal-research/opinion-132019-draft-list-competent-supervisory-authority-france-regarding-processing" target="_blank">Opinion 13/2019 on the draft list of the competent supervisory authority of France regarding the processing operations exempt from the requirement of a data protection impact assessment (Article 35(5) GDPR)</a>; and</li><li><a href="https://platform.dataguidance.com/legal-research/opinion-92018-draft-list-competent-supervisory-authority-france-regarding-0" target="_blank">Opinion 9/2018 on the draft list of the competent supervisory authority of France regarding the processing operations subject to the requirement of a data protection impact assessment (Article 35.4 GDPR) (25 September 2018)</a>.</li></ul><div name="2.BLACKLISTS" data-unique="2.BLACKLISTS"></div><h2>2. BLACKLISTS</h2><div name="2.1.GDPRandtheGuidelines" data-unique="2.1.GDPRandtheGuidelines"></div><h3>2.1. GDPR and the Guidelines</h3><p>Article 35(1) of the GDPR mandates that a DPIA is required where a type of processing, in particular using new technologies, and taking into account the nature, scope, context and purposes of the processing, is likely to result in a high risk to the rights and freedoms of natural persons, the controller must, prior to the processing, carry out an assessment of the impact of the envisaged processing operations on the protection of personal data. A single assessment may address a set of similar processing operations that present similar high risks.</p><p>A DPIA is required in the case of (Article 35(3) of the GDPR):</p><ul><li>a systematic and extensive evaluation of personal aspects relating to natural persons which is based on automated processing, including profiling, and on which decisions are based that produce legal effects concerning the natural person or similarly significantly affect the natural person;</li><li>processing on a large scale of special categories of data referred to in Article 9(1) of the GDPR, or of personal data relating to criminal convictions and offences referred to in Article 10 of the GDPR; or</li><li>a systematic monitoring of a publicly accessible area on a large scale.</li></ul><p>The Guidelines highlight that Article 35(3) of the GDPR is a non-exhaustive list. The Guidelines also provide nine criteria to consider when determining whether the processing is likely to result in a high risk:</p><ul><li>evaluation and scoring;</li><li>automated-decision making with legal or similar significant effect;</li><li>systematic monitoring;</li><li>sensitive data or data of a highly personal nature;</li><li>data processed on a large scale;</li><li>matching or combining datasets;</li><li>data concerning vulnerable data subjects;</li><li>innovative use or applying new technological or organisational solutions; or</li><li>when the processing itself prevents data subjects from exercising a right or using a service or a contract.</li></ul><div name="2.2.NationalDPIABlacklist" data-unique="2.2.NationalDPIABlacklist"></div><h3><a id="column-1" name="column-1"></a><a id="column-11" name="column-11"></a><a id="column-10" name="column-10"></a><a id="column-9" name="column-9"></a><a id="column-8" name="column-8"></a><a id="column-7" name="column-7"></a><a id="column-6" name="column-6"></a><a id="column-6" name="column-6"></a><a id="column-5" name="column-5"></a><a id="column-4" name="column-4"></a><a id="column-3" name="column-3"></a><a id="column-2" name="column-2"></a><a id="column-12" name="column-12"></a>2.2. National DPIA Blacklist</h3><p><u>The Guidelines set out that the controller can consider that a processing meeting two criteria would require a DPIA to be carried out. However, in some cases, a data controller can consider that a processing meeting only one of these criteria requires a DPIA.</u></p><p>The France Blacklist provides that the following types of processing operations require a DPIA:</p><ul><li>health data carried out by healthcare establishments or medico-social establishments for the care of individuals, referencing the sensitive data and vulnerable data subjects criteria from the Guidelines;</li><li>genetic data of vulnerable data subjects, such as patients, employees, and children, referencing the sensitive data and vulnerable data subjects criteria from the Guidelines;</li><li>profiling of data subjects for human resources purposes, referencing the profiling and vulnerable data subjects criteria from the Guidelines;</li><li>systematic monitoring of employees' activities, referencing the systematic monitoring and vulnerable data subjects criteria from the Guidelines;</li><li>management of alerts and reports (whistleblowing) in the field of health and social matters, referencing the vulnerable data subjects, evaluation or scoring, and sensitive data criteria from the Guidelines;</li><li>management of alerts and reports (whistleblowing) in the context of professional matters, referencing the vulnerable data subjects, evaluation or scoring, and sensitive data criteria from the Guidelines;</li><li>health data necessary for establishing a data warehouse or register, referencing the sensitive data and vulnerable data subjects criteria from the Guidelines;</li><li>profiling of persons that may lead to their exclusion from a contract or to suspension or termination, referencing the evaluation or scoring and the combined data sets criteria from the Guidelines;</li><li>mutualised processing of personal data which is related to verified contractual breaches which are likely to lead to the exclusion of the data subject from a contract or the contract's suspension or termination, referencing the combined data sets, and preventing data subjects from exercising a right criteria from the Guidelines;</li><li>profiling using data coming from external sources, referencing the combined data set and evaluation or scoring criteria from the Guidelines;</li><li>biometric data of vulnerable data subjects for recognising the data subject, referencing the sensitive data and vulnerable data subjects criteria of the Guidelines;</li><li>processing related to evaluation and management of social housing applications, referencing the sensitive data and evaluation or scoring criteria from the Guidelines;</li><li>processing for social or medico-social care, referencing the sensitive data, evaluation or scoring, and vulnerable data subjects criteria from the Guidelines; and</li><li>location data on a large scale, referencing sensitive data and large scale criteria from the Guidelines.</li></ul><p>However, the France Blacklist provides that this list is not exhaustive and that, in accordance with Article 35(1) of the GDPR, a DPIA should be carried out whenever the processing is likely to result in a high risk to the rights and freedoms of individuals.</p><div name="3.EXCEPTIONS" data-unique="3.EXCEPTIONS"></div><h2>3. EXCEPTIONS</h2><div name="3.1.TheGDPRandtheGuidelines" data-unique="3.1.TheGDPRandtheGuidelines"></div><h3>3.1. The GDPR and the Guidelines</h3><p>A DPIA is not required:</p><ul><li>where the processing is not likely to result in a high risk to the rights and freedoms of natural persons (Article 35(1) of the GDPR);</li><li>when the nature, scope, context and purposes of the processing are very similar to the processing for which a DPIA has alreadybeen carried out. In such cases, results of DPIAs for similar processing can be used (Article 35(1) of the GDPR);</li><li>when the processing operations have been checked by a supervisory authority before May 2018 in specific conditions that have not changed (Page 13 of the Guidelines);</li><li>where processing pursuant to Article 6(1)(c) or (e) of the GDPR has a legal basis in Union law or in the law of the Member State to which the controller is subject, that law regulates the specific processing operation or set of operations in question and where a DPIA has already been carried out as part of a general impact assessment in the context of the adoption of that legal basis, Article 35(1) to (7) of the GDPR will not apply unless Member States deem it to be necessary to carry out such an assessment prior to processing activities (Article 35(10) of the GDPR); or</li><li>where the processing is included in a Whitelist issued by the supervisory authority (Article 35(5) of the GDPR).</li></ul><div name="3.2.NationalDPIAWhitelist" data-unique="3.2.NationalDPIAWhitelist"></div><h3><a id="column-13" name="column-13"></a>3.2. National DPIA Whitelist</h3><p>The France Whitelist provides that the following types of processing activities do not require a DPIA:</p><ul><li>those implemented in accordance with the conditions laid down in the applicable texts, specifically for human resources purposes by employers with fewer than 250 people, provided that profiling is not used;</li><li>in the management of the relationship with suppliers;</li><li>those implemented in accordance with the conditions specified in the law relating to the management of the electoral register of municipalities;</li><li>in the management of working committees and councils;</li><li>carried out by an association, foundation or any other non-profit institution for the management of its members and donors in the framework of its regular activities, provided that the data is not sensitive;</li><li>processing of health data which is necessary for the care of a patient by an individual healthcare professional in a medical practice, a pharmacy or a medical biology laboratory;</li><li>by lawyers in the individual practice of their profession;</li><li>by the clerks of commercial courts for the purpose of carrying out their activity;</li><li>by notaries for the purpose of carrying out their notarial activity and the drafting of notarial office documents;</li><li>by local authorities, as well as legal persons covered by public and private law, for the management of schools, as well as extracurricular and early childhood services;</li><li>solely for the purpose of managing physical access controls and schedules for calculating of working times, in the exclusion of any biometric device and provided that the processing does not reveal sensitive data or data of a highly personal nature; and</li><li>processing implemented in the framework of transport activities, mandatory by law and restricted to the sole purpose of preventing drivers from operating vehicles while under the influence of alcohol or narcotics.</li></ul><p>It should be further noted that the EDPB issued, on 22 April 2020, its <a href="https://platform.dataguidance.com/legal-research/opinion-72020-draft-list-competent-supervisory-authority-france-regarding-processing" target="_blank">Opinion 7/2020 on the Draft List of the Competent Supervisory Authority of France regarding the Processing Operations Exempt from the Requirement of a Data Protection Impact Assessment (Article 35(5) GDPR)</a> ('Opinion 7/2020'), which recommends, regarding the management of commercial activities,&nbsp;reducing the scope of the Whitelist by covering only business-to-consumer relations,&nbsp;and excluding the processing of sensitive data or data of highly personal nature from the Whitelist.</p><div name="4.HOWTOCONDUCTADPIA" data-unique="4.HOWTOCONDUCTADPIA"></div><h2>4. HOW TO CONDUCT A DPIA</h2><p>The CNIL has launched version 3.0 of its&nbsp;PIA <a href="https://platform.dataguidance.com/legal-research/tool-cnil-pia-tool" target="_blank">assessment tool</a>&nbsp;which can be accessed online <a href="https://github.com/LINCnil/pia" target="_blank">here</a> or <a href="https://github.com/LINCnil/pia-back" target="_blank">here</a>, or downloaded for Windows <a href="https://github.com/LINCnil/pia-app/releases/download/v2.2.0/PIA.Setup.2.2.0.exe" target="_blank">here</a>, for Mac OS <a href="https://github.com/LINCnil/pia-app/releases/download/v2.2.0/PIA-2.2.0.dmg" target="_blank">here</a>, and for Linux <a href="https://github.com/LINCnil/pia-app/releases/download/v2.2.0/PIA-2.2.0.AppImage" target="_blank">here</a>.</p><p>In addition, the CNIL has published:</p><ul><li>French version of the France Blacklist, which includes specific examples of processing activities which require a DPIA (only available in French <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/sites/default/files/atoms/files/liste-traitements-aipd-requise.pdf" target="_blank">here</a>);</li><li><a href="https://platform.dataguidance.com/legal-research/template-pia-1-methodology" target="_blank">PIA Methodology template</a>;</li><li><a href="https://platform.dataguidance.com/legal-research/template-pia-2-templates" target="_blank">PIA templates</a>; and</li><li><a href="https://platform.dataguidance.com/legal-research/template-privacy-impact-assessment-application-iot-devices" target="_blank">Template on PIA in the context of Internet of Things devices</a>.</li></ul><div name="5.PENALTIES" data-unique="5.PENALTIES"></div><h2>5. PENALTIES</h2><p><strong>GDPR</strong></p><p>Failure to carry out a DPIA when the processing is subject to a DPIA (Article 35(1) and (3) to (4) of the GDPR), carrying out a DPIA in an incorrect way (Article 35(2) and (7) to (9) of the GDPR), or failing to consult the competent supervisory authority where required (Article 36(3)(e) of the GDPR), can result in an administrative fine of up to €10 million, or in the case of an undertaking, up to 2% of the total worldwide annual turnover of the preceding financial year, whichever is higher.</p></div></div></div>